BIAS 1  ANCHORING BIAS 
"The first rate you see shapes every comparison that follows — but it doesn't have to." 
Anchoring is the brain's tendency to give disproportionate weight to the f irst number it encounters. In the 
mortgage process, the f irst quote you receive can become your unconscious ref erence point — even when better 
rates exist in the market. Understanding this bias puts you back in control. 
 
易  SELF-ASSESSMENT QUIZ 
Q1: When you receive your first mortgage quote, what do you do? 
A)  I immediately research current market rates to establish an independent benchmark. 
B)  I compare it to rates I've heard about generally, then seek more quotes. 
C)  I use it as my main ref erence point and measure every other quote against it. 
Q2: If a lender drops their rate from 7.4% to 7.0% during negotiation, you feel: 
A)  Neutral — I need to verif y where actual market rates stand bef ore reacting. 
B)  Mildly relieved, though I'd still want to compare externally. 
C)  Like I've won a signif icant negotiation and should move f orward quickly. 
Q3: How many lenders do you plan to get quotes from? 
A)  At least 4–5, ideally on the same day f or accurate comparison. 
B)  2–3 over a f ew weeks, as my schedule allows. 
C)  Probably 1–2 — whoever seems most trustworthy and f amiliar. 
Scoring: Mostly C answers = Higher Risk  •  Mostly A/B answers = Lower Risk. Use your result to calibrate how much 
extra attention to give this bias. 
 
⚠  WORST-CASE SCENARIO: The Approximately $16,750 Anchor 
THE SITUATION 
First-time buyer Marcus visits his bank on Day 1. They quote 7.45% on a $350,000 30-year f ixed loan and 
tell him it's competitive f or his credit prof ile. Marcus f eels reassured by a f amiliar institution. 
* All case studies are fictional composites created for educational illustration. Any resemblance to actual individuals, lenders, or 
