THE BIAS IN ACTION 
Marcus anchors to 7.45%. When an online lender later quotes 6.85%, Marcus feels like he's getting a deal 
— without knowing the true market rate that week was 6.65%. He locks at 6.85% believing he won the 
negotiation. 
THE ESTIMATED DOLLAR COST* 
The dif f erence between 6.85% and 6.65% on $350,000 over 30 years is approximately $16,750 in 
additional interest, based on these illustrative assumptions. Had Marcus used market rate data as his 
anchor instead of  his bank's opening quote, he had a strong case to negotiate to 6.65% or lower. 
THE LESSON 
Never let a lender's opening quote set your ref erence point. Your anchor should be objective market data 
— such as the Freddie Mac Primary Mortgage Market Survey. (Note: The Freddie Mac survey is a widely 

