BIAS 2  PRESENT BIAS 
"Focusing only on monthly payment can cost tens of thousands over your loan's lifetime." 
Present  bias describes our tendency to over-value immediate, tangible costs and undervalue f uture 
consequences — even when  those f uture consequences are much larger.  In  mortgages, this of ten means 
optimizing f or the lowest monthly payment while overlooking the total cost of  the loan over its f ull term. 
 
易  SELF-ASSESSMENT QUIZ 
Q1: When evaluating loan options, your first question is usually: 
A)  What is the total interest I'll pay over the lif e of  this loan? 
B)  What is the APR, and how do these loans compare on total cost? 
C)  What will my monthly payment be? 
Q2: A lender offers to extend your loan from 20 to 30 years, saving you $280/month. You: 
A)  Decline and calculate the total interest dif f erence bef ore making any decision. 
B)  Ask to see both the monthly savings and the total interest comparison side by side. 
C)  Accept — $280/month in savings is meaningf ul and I could use the breathing room. 
Q3: If your lender offers to roll your closing costs into the loan, you: 
A)  Decline and pref er to pay closing costs upf ront to avoid compounding them. 
B)  Ask to see exactly how much this adds to your total interest paid over the loan lif e. 
C)  Accept — it reduces what I need at closing and the monthly increase seems small. 
Scoring: Mostly C answers = Higher Risk  •  Mostly A/B answers = Lower Risk. Use your result to calibrate how much 
extra attention to give this bias. 
 
⚠  WORST-CASE SCENARIO: The Approximately $208,100 Monthly Mirage 

Mo Phanor  |  NMLS# 2420740  |  MLO — Mortgage Decision Coach  |  404-692-2444  |  talktomo@mophanor.com          Page 5 
THE SITUATION 
First-time buyer Priya qualif ies f or both a 20-year loan at 6.75% and a 30-year loan at 7.1% on her 
$350,000 purchase. Her lender presents both options but highlights the 30-year: 'The payment dif f erence 
is $309/month — that's real money every month.' 
 Note: The relief of lower monthly payments is real — and for some buyers, a 30-year loan is genuinely the 
right choice. The key is making that decision with full information, not just the number that feels most immediate. 
THE BIAS IN ACTION 
Priya f ocuses entirely on the monthly payment difference. $309/month f eels enormous and immediate — 
the extra $208,000 in total interest feels abstract and thirty years away. Present bias wins: she chooses the 
30-year loan. 
THE ESTIMATED DOLLAR COST* 
30-year at 7.1%: estimated total interest paid = approximately $496,800. 20-year at 6.75%: estimated total 
interest paid = approximately $288,700. Based on these illustrative assumptions, the present-bias-driven 
choice cost Priya approximately $208,100 in additional total interest — in exchange for $309 lower monthly 
payments she may have been able to manage with modest adjustments. 
THE LESSON 
Always ask your lender to show a side-by-side comparison of  total interest paid — not just monthly 
payment. The monthly difference will feel large; the lifetime cost difference will feel abstract. Your goal is to 
evaluate both numbers with equal weight. 
 
 Tactic to Be Aware Of ✅ Your Counter-Move 
Presenting only monthly payment comparisons, never 
total interest over the full term 
Ask: 'Show me total interest paid for each option over 
the full loan term.' 
Rolling closing costs into the loan to minimize upfront 
cash ('seamless!') 
Calculate: closing costs rolled in × interest rate × loan 
years = actual cost of 'convenience.' It's almost always 
more significant than it appears. 
Extending the loan term to make a property feel 
affordable when it may not be 
If you can only qualify at a monthly payment with a 30-
year term, ask yourself whether your long-term 
financial plan can absorb the total interest cost. 
 
 
 
BIAS 3  CHOICE OVERLOAD 
"Too many options at once can lead to paralysis — or a default decision that isn't right for you." 
When  f aced with more options than we can comf ortably evaluate, we typically do one of  two things: we f reeze 
entirely, or we  def ault to the most f amiliar, most recently seen, or most strongly recommended option — 
regardless of  whether it's actually optimal. Arriving with a clear f ramework prevents both outcomes. 
 
易  SELF-ASSESSMENT QUIZ 
Q1: Before your first lender meeting, your loan type criteria is: 
A)  Clearly def ined — I know my pref erred term, rate type, and down payment range. 
B)  Somewhat def ined — I know I want a f ixed rate but I'm open on other details. 

