BIAS 4  LOSS AVERSION 
"Fear of losing the home — or the deal — can lead to choices you'll carry for 30 years." 
Research  consistently shows that losses f eel approximately twice as painf ul as equivalent gains f eel good. In a 
competitive real estate market, this means that the f ear of  losing a home can drive buyers to overpay, waive 
critical protections, and make impulsive decisions that result in f ar larger f inancial losses than the one they were 
trying to avoid. 
 
易  SELF-ASSESSMENT QUIZ 
Q1: You've lost two homes in bidding wars this month. On your third offer, you: 
A)  Of f er what the home is actually worth to you based on recent comparable sales — no more. 
B)  Go $5,000–$10,000 above asking if  you truly love the home, but maintain your ceiling. 
C)  Of f er whatever it takes and waive contingencies — the emotional cost of losing again feels too high. 
Q2: Your rate lock expires in 3 days and rates have risen slightly. Your lender offers a 30-day 
extension for $400. You: 
A)  Pay the $400 — it's a reasonable hedge against f urther rate increases. 
B)  Evaluate whether a potential rate increase would cost more than $400, then decide. 
C)  Hesitate to pay $400 f or something you f eel you've already paid f or — and let it expire. 
Q3: The home inspection comes back with $8,000 in repairs on a home you love. You: 
A)  Negotiate a price reduction or seller credit — or walk away if  they won't budge. 
B)  Feel the pull of  not wanting to lose the deal, but still raise the repair issue with the seller. 
C)  Waive the repair request immediately to secure the home bef ore another of f er appears. 
Scoring: Mostly C answers = Higher Risk  •  Mostly A/B answers = Lower Risk. Use your result to calibrate how much 
extra attention to give this bias. 
 
⚠  WORST-CASE SCENARIO: The Approximately $47,000 Panic Bid 
THE SITUATION 
Buyer Tanya has lost 3 homes in bidding wars. She is exhausted and emotionally drained. A 4th home 
comes on at $340,000. She and her agent estimate fair value at $352,000. A competing of f er comes in at 
$360,000. 
 Note: After three failed bids, the exhaustion Tanya felt was completely real and understandable. Loss 
aversion is most powerful when we're already emotionally depleted — which is exactly when a pre-set ceiling 
matters most. 
THE BIAS IN ACTION 

Mo Phanor  |  NMLS# 2420740  |  MLO — Mortgage Decision Coach  |  404-692-2444  |  talktomo@mophanor.com          Page 8 
Loss aversion and bid-f atigue combine. The pain of  losing a 4th home f eels unbearable. Tanya of f ers 
$387,000 — $35,000 above the competing bid and $47,000 above f air market value — and waives the 
inspection contingency. She wins. 
THE ESTIMATED DOLLAR COST* 
Tanya paid $387,000 f or a home estimated at $352,000 at purchase: approximately $35,000 overpayment, 
based on these illustrative assumptions. In the f irst year, she discovers approximately $12,000 in HVAC 
and roof  issues she could not negotiate because she had waived her inspection contingency. Estimated 
total loss-aversion cost: approximately $47,000+. 
THE LESSON 
Set a hard maximum price in writing before every showing — and keep it where you can see it. When you 
f eel the urge to exceed it, call your mortgage coach before acting. The pain of losing a home typically fades 
within 48–72 hours. An overpayment of  $47,000 stays with you f or the lif e of  your loan. 
 
 Tactic to Be Aware Of ✅ Your Counter-Move 
'There are 4 other offers — you need to decide today' 
urgency creation 
Urgency is rarely as absolute as presented. Ask: 'What 
is the written offer deadline?' Legitimate deadlines are 
always documentable. 
Encouraging appraisal gap coverage that far exceeds 
the home's risk-adjusted value 
Decide your maximum appraisal gap in advance — as 
a specific dollar figure you've thought through, not a 
number chosen under pressure. 
'You don't want to lose this one too' language after 
multiple failed offers 
Recognize this as a loss-aversion trigger. It may be 
unintentional — but it's worth naming out loud to 
yourself so you can respond from your framework, not 
your emotions. 
 
