⚠  WORST-CASE SCENARIO: The Approximately $33,850 Loyalty Tax 
THE SITUATION 
First-time buyer Daniel has banked with a major national bank f or 11 years. He calls them f irst f or a 
mortgage quote and receives 7.25% on a 30-year f ixed $350,000 loan. The loan officer mentions a 0.125% 
loyalty discount, bringing it to 7.125%. Daniel f eels well taken care of  and doesn't shop f urther. 
 Note: The trust Daniel had built with his bank over 11 years was genuine — and that familiarity made it easy 
to stop looking. Status quo bias is most powerful when the current option feels 'good enough.' 
THE BIAS IN ACTION 
Status quo bias and f amiliarity combine: the bank is trusted, the relationship is real, switching f eels 
unnecessary and complicated. Daniel doesn't know that a regional credit union in his area is of f ering 
6.75% on identical loan terms that same week. 
THE ESTIMATED DOLLAR COST* 
7.125% vs. 6.75% on $350,000 over 30 years: the rate difference costs Daniel approximately $88/month. 
Over 30 years, that's an estimated $32,050 in additional interest. Adding the typically higher origination 
f ees at national banks vs. credit unions (approximately $1,800 in this scenario): estimated total loyalty cost 
= approximately $33,850, based on these illustrative assumptions. 
THE LESSON 
The solution isn't to blindly shop — it's to shop smart. A Mortgage Decision Coach can pull current market 
benchmarks, show you what your profile actually qualifies for, and help you evaluate any quote you receive 
— without you having to decode the jargon alone. That's exactly what a Mortgage Clarity Call is designed 
to do. (Note: Multiple mortgage-related credit inquiries within a 14–45 day window are typically grouped as 
a single inquiry under rate-shopping protections used by major credit bureaus. Shopping multiple lenders 
need not harm your credit score.) 
 
 Tactic to Be Aware Of ✅ Your Counter-Move 
'It's  easier to keep everything in one place' 
convenience bundling pitch 
Convenience is worth something — but calculate what 
'easier' actually costs you in rate differential before you 
accept it as a reason. 
Loyalty discounts that still leave your rate above the 
market average 
A discount that keeps you 0.3% above market is a 
reduced overcharge, not a benefit. Verify against the 
Freddie Mac benchmark. 

