BIAS 6  SUNK COST FALLACY 
"Past time and money spent are not reasons to proceed with a bad deal." 
The  sunk cost f allacy leads people to continue poor decisions because of  prior investment — time, money, or 
emotional energy — rather  than evaluating  current  and f uture costs rationally. In homebuying, sunk costs can 
work both unconsciously (in the buyer's own mind) and deliberately (as a  closing strategy) to prevent rational exits 
f rom situations that deserve a harder look. 
 
易  SELF-ASSESSMENT QUIZ 
Q1: After 5 weeks of working with a lender, you discover their closing costs are $4,200 above the 
original Loan Estimate. You: 
A)  Formally challenge the fee increase or walk away — signif icant unexplained increases may warrant 
review with a HUD-approved housing counselor. 
B)  Negotiate hard on the f ees, evaluate the lender's explanation, and decide based on the outcome. 
C)  Proceed — you've invested 5 weeks, your appraisal is paid, and your move-in date is set. 
Q2: You paid $600 for a home inspection and the report reveals $28,000 in structural issues. The 
seller won't negotiate. You: 
A)  Walk away — you just saved $28,000+ and your $600 is gone regardless of  what you decide. 
B)  Evaluate whether the home is still a good deal at the adjusted price, f actoring in the repairs. 
C)  Proceed — the inspection f ee, application time, and energy spent make walking away f eel like 
wasting everything. 
Q3: Three months into your home search, you realize the neighborhood you've focused on no 
longer fits your needs. You: 
A)  Pivot immediately — nothing you've done to this point obligates you to the wrong neighborhood. 
B)  Spend a f ew more weeks in the area to be certain bef ore redirecting your search. 
C)  Stay the course — you've built agent relationships here and starting f resh f eels overwhelming. 
Scoring: Mostly C answers = Higher Risk  •  Mostly A/B answers = Lower Risk. Use your result to calibrate how much 
extra attention to give this bias. 
 
⚠  WORST-CASE SCENARIO: The Approximately $36,125 Closing Trap 
THE SITUATION 
Buyer Keisha has spent 7 weeks in underwriting with a lender. She has paid a $750 appraisal f ee. The 
moving company is booked. Her Closing Disclosure, received 3 days before closing, shows an interest rate 
0.375% higher than the originally quoted rate of 6.5% — bringing it to 6.875% — and $4,800 in f ees not on 
her original Loan Estimate. 

Mo Phanor  |  NMLS# 2420740  |  MLO — Mortgage Decision Coach  |  404-692-2444  |  talktomo@mophanor.com          Page 11 
 Note: The logistical weight Keisha was carrying — 7 weeks of paperwork, a booked moving truck, an excited 
family — made 'just a little more' feel like the path of least resistance. That is exactly how sunk cost pressure is 
designed to feel. 
THE BIAS IN ACTION 
The sunk cost fallacy activates powerfully: 7 weeks of effort, $750 already spent, boxes packed, moving 
truck booked. Her lender says 'this is normal — rates moved slightly during underwriting.' Keisha f eels she 
can't walk away now. She proceeds. 
THE ESTIMATED DOLLAR COST* 
Based on a quoted rate of  6.5% increased by 0.375% to 6.875% on $350,000 over 30 years: the rate 
increase adds approximately $31,325 in additional interest. Combined with $4,800 in excess f ees, the 
estimated total sunk-cost-driven cost = approximately $36,125. The $750 appraisal was the only money 
truly sunk. Everything else could have been restarted. (Note: Signif icant unexplained changes between 
your Loan Estimate and Closing Disclosure may warrant a review with a HUD-approved housing 
counselor. You also have the right to f ile a complaint with the CFPB if  you believe your rights under 
RESPA or TILA have been violated.) 
THE LESSON 
The only money you truly lose by walking away at closing is your appraisal fee (approximately $500–$800). 
Everything else can restart. When you compare $750 to $36,125, the math is clear. Review your Closing 
Disclosure the moment it's issued — required 3 business days before closing — and compare every line to 
your original Loan Estimate. Having a Mortgage Decision Coach review your Loan Estimate and Closing 
Disclosure side-by-side takes the guesswork out of knowing when something is wrong — and gives you 
the conf idence to act on it. 
 
