the guesswork out of knowing when something is 
wrong. 
 
 
 
BIAS 7  RECENCY  BIAS 
"Last month's rate trend is not a forecast. Your buying timeline should be driven by readiness 
— not momentum." 
Recency  bias causes us to overweight recent events and assume they predict f uture patterns. Buyers who watch 
rates f all f or three weeks assume they'll keep f alling; buyers who watch prices rise f or 18 months assume they'll 
always rise. Both assumptions routinely lead to costly decisions when the pattern eventually reverses. 
 

Mo Phanor  |  NMLS# 2420740  |  MLO — Mortgage Decision Coach  |  404-692-2444  |  talktomo@mophanor.com          Page 12 
易  SELF-ASSESSMENT QUIZ 
Q1: Mortgage rates have dropped 0.4% over the past 3 weeks. You: 
A)  Note it as one data point and continue evaluating based on your readiness and 12-month context. 
B)  Feel some additional urgency to lock — but check with your mortgage coach bef ore acting. 
C)  Rush to lock immediately — this trend could reverse and you don't want to miss the window. 
Q2: Home prices in your target area have risen 14% year-over-year for 2 consecutive years. You: 
A)  Account f or the trend but stress-test your purchase assuming f lat or declining appreciation. 
B)  Feel more conf ident buying near the top of  your budget — appreciation will build equity. 
C)  Stretch your budget signif icantly — prices here always go up, and waiting means paying more. 
Q3: A friend tells you they just locked a great rate last week. You: 
A)  Note it as one anecdote and check current rates independently bef ore drawing any conclusions. 
B)  Feel mild urgency but wait to speak with your mortgage coach bef ore making any decisions. 
C)  Feel signif icant urgency to act now bef ore rates move higher. 
Scoring: Mostly C answers = Higher Risk  •  Mostly A/B answers = Lower Risk. Use your result to calibrate how much 
extra attention to give this bias. 
 
⚠  WORST-CASE SCENARIO: The Approximately $51,000 Trend Assumption 
THE SITUATION 
First-time buyers Marcus and his partner have watched prices in their target suburb rise 16% f or 24 
consecutive months. In early 2022, they stretch their budget to $390,000 — $55,000 above their original 
ceiling — convinced that 'prices here never stop going up' and that waiting means paying even more. 
 Note: Two full years of rising prices makes 'this is just how this market works' feel like objective fact. Recency 
bias doesn't feel like bias when the evidence has been consistent for that long — which is what makes it so worth 
examining. 
THE BIAS IN ACTION 
Recency bias presents 24 months of  appreciation data as a permanent f uture reality. Marcus pays 
$390,000 and f inances $370,500 at 5.5%. Eighteen months later, the neighborhood corrects 13% and 
comparable homes sell f or $339,000. Marcus and his partner are underwater. 
THE ESTIMATED DOLLAR COST* 
Estimated overpayment relative to post-correction value: approximately $51,000, based on these 
illustrative assumptions. Refinancing in 2024 is not viable without PMI since equity is now negative. The 
recency-bias-driven budget stretch cost approximately $51,000 in equity destruction plus ongoing PMI 
costs of  approximately $250/month until the market recovers. 
THE LESSON 
Evaluate prices and rates over 10-year historical windows, not 12–24 month windows. Never stretch your 
ceiling based on recent trend momentum alone. Markets revert — sometimes sharply and quickly. 
 
 Tactic to Be Aware Of ✅ Your Counter-Move 
'Rates are at a historic low right now — this won't last' 
urgency framing 
Ask: 'What have rates averaged over the past 10 
years?' Put the current rate in genuine historical 
context before making any urgency-driven decisions. 

