Showing only recent appreciation comparables without 
long-term price history 
Request 10-year price history for any neighborhood 
before stretching your budget on appreciation 
assumptions. 
'Everyone is buying right now' social proof creating 
Fear of Missing Out-driven urgency 
Recognize Fear of Missing Out as a recency bias 
trigger. Your timeline must be driven by financial 
readiness — not market momentum or social 
comparison. 
 
 
 
  Lender Awareness Tactics: The Master Checklist 
These  tactics exist in the marketplace and are documented in consumer protection literature. The majority of  
mortgage prof essionals are ethical and serve their clients well. Use this checklist as a protective awareness tool 
— not as a characterization  of  the industry. 
 
Tactic What It Sounds  Like Why  It Matters & What To Do 
Bait  & Switch  Rate 'Rates  moved slightly during 
underwriting' (Sunk Cost) 
Significant unexplained rate increases after a rate lock 
warrant a written explanation. Review your Loan Estimate 
vs. Closing Disclosure carefully; meaningful discrepancies 
may  warrant review with a housing counselor. 
False  Urgency 'This rate expires tonight / there 
are  3 other buyers' (Loss 
Aversion) 
Legitimate lenders allow adequate decision time. Ask for 
the offer deadline in writing. Artificial urgency is designed to 
bypass your evaluation process. 
Monthly  Payment 
Focus 
'Your payment is only $2,150!' 
with no total cost shown 
(Present Bias) 
Always ask for total interest paid over the loan life. If they 
won't show it, calculate it yourself. 
Anchoring  High First quote 0.4–0.6%  above 
market  with negotiation room 
built in (Anchoring) 
Research the Freddie Mac Primary Mortgage Market 
Survey for an objective benchmark. (Local rates may vary.) 
Option Flooding Presenting 6–10 loan products 
simultaneously without filtering 
(Choice Overload) 
Say:  'I'm  only evaluating [your pre-set criteria] today. 
Loyalty  Inflation 'Your loyalty discount brings you 
to X%' — still above market 
(Status  Quo) 
A  loyalty discount that doesn't close the gap to current 
market  rates is a reduced overcharge. Verify against 
independent benchmarks. 
Fee  Drip  Disclosure New  fees appearing close to 
closing after significant time 
invested (Sunk Cost) 
Compare every line of your Closing Disclosure to your 
original Loan Estimate. Changes beyond legal tolerance 
may  warrant professional review. 
Trend  FOMO 'Prices/rates are  moving fast — 
buyers who wait always regret 
it' (Recency Bias) 
Review historical context before any trend-based urgency 
influences your timeline. 
Cost Rolling 'We can roll your closing costs 
into the loan so you bring less to 
closing' (Present Bias) 
Calculate:  (closing costs) × (interest rate) × (years) = actual 
cost of rolling. It's almost always more significant than 
presented. 
Complexity 
Weaponization 
Intentional use of jargon to 
make  comparison difficult 
(Choice Overload) 
You have the right to a plain-language explanation of every 
fee  and every loan term. Request it in writing if needed. 

